Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

Slovakia has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Slovakia, see Return to the UK
Entry and borders
Slovakia has closed its international airports at Bratislava, Kosice and Poprad to scheduled passenger flights.
As of 13 March, entry to Slovakia is permitted only for Slovak citizens foreigners with proof of residency in Slovakia, and other foreign nationals under certain conditions.
As of 6 April, it is mandatory to pre-register with the Slovak authorities 72 hours in advance of travel to Slovakia and then on arrival enter mandatory quarantine in a government facility for 14 days. Once tested negative for COVID-19, the remainder of the 14 days can be spent in self-isolation at home.
If you qualify under one of the exceptions for mandatory quarantine in a government facility, you must still self-isolate at home for 14 days or risk incurring a fine of up to €1,659. For a list of exceptions and requirements, check the website of the Slovak government.
The following land border entry points to Slovakia are operational, but this can change at short notice. For the latest information, including advice for cross-border workers (so called ‘pendlers’), see the Slovak police Facebook page (in Slovak only). You should also check the FCO Travel Advice for any country you wish to transit on your way to Slovakia:
From Austria: Jarovce-Kittsee (motorway),Bratislava Petrzalka- Berg (old road) and Moravsky Sv. Jan – Hohenau (0500-midnight)
From the Czech Republic: Svrcinovec - Mosty u Jablunkova, Makov - Bíla-Bumbalka, Lysa pod Makytou – Strelna, Horne Srnie - Brumov - Bylnice, Drietoma - Stary Hrozenkov, Moravske Lieskove – Strani, Vrbovce - Velka nad Velickou, Skalica - Sudomerice (new road), Holic – Hodonin, Brodske Breclav
From Poland: Vysny Komarnik- Barwinek and Trstena-Chyzne
From Ukraine: Ubla- Maly Bereznyj (entry for pedestrians is limited)
From Hungary: Slovenske Nove Mesto – Satoraljaujhely, Milhost – Tornyosnemeti, ahy – Parassapuszta, Kral – Banreve, Cunovo-Rajka, Sturovo - Esztergom, Komarno - Komarom, Siatorska Bukovinka - Salgotarjan Somoskoujfalu, Slovenske Darmoty - Balassagyarmat, Hosovce – Tornanadaska (0600 to 1800)
For information on how to return to the UK from Slovakia, see Return to the UK
Local measures
On 12 March, the Slovak government declared a State of Emergency and announced a range of restrictions on travel and events.
Local public transport is running on a reduced timetable.
It is mandatory to wear a mask or otherwise cover your nose and mouth when travelling on public transport and anywhere outside the home. The exceptions to wearing a face mask outside are only for: children under 2 years; people from the same household walking in the countryside as long as they remain 20 metres from others; people diagnosed with serious autism; people in a car if they are from the same household.
Most public gatherings remain banned, including sporting events, cinemas and theatres. All kindergartens, schools, universities, swimming pools and spas are closed until further notice.
As part of a phased lifting of restrictions, from 6 May the following services are open, but with social distancing and hygiene measures in place:
shops (except the largest shopping malls), supermarkets, pharmacies, outdoor markets
some outdoor sports venues for non-contact sports, without changing rooms/toilets and without spectators
car dealerships (new and second-hand)
short and long-term accommodation without catering
hairdressers, pedicure and manicure services
outdoor tourist attractions, outdoor areas of bars and restaurants; museums, galleries, libraries and exhibition halls, and church services
taxi services
For more information and a full list of businesses and activities open to the public check the Slovak Public Health Authority (in Slovak only) and the Slovak government Coronavirus website.
